## Before Starting Any Feature

Run this checklist. Do not proceed until all boxes are checked.

```
□ I have read the relevant User Task(s) from .utad/user-task-tree.md
□ At least one Test Instance exists for this feature in .utad/test-instances/
□ The Test Instance has Happy Path, Failure, and Experience Quality coverage
□ The coverage-matrix.md has been updated to include this Test Instance
□ I am working at the correct task granularity (Task level, not Action level)
```

---

## Agent Boundary System

### ✅ Always do (no confirmation needed)
- Read `.utad/` files at the start of any feature work
- Reference the corresponding Test Instance before writing implementation
- Use the domain language from Test Instances when naming code constructs
- Update `coverage-matrix.md` after completing a feature
- Run acceptance criteria from Test Instances against your implementation

### ⚠️ Ask before doing
- Implementing something that has no corresponding Test Instance
  → Ask: "I don't see a Test Instance for this. Should I create one first with /utad-test?"
- Discovering that two Test Instances appear to conflict
  → Ask: "TI-XXX and TI-YYY seem to describe contradictory behaviour. Which takes precedence?"
- Proposing to delete or substantially change a Test Instance
  → Ask: "This change would invalidate TI-XXX. Is the user requirement actually changing?"

### 🚫 Never do
- Write implementation code for a new feature without a Test Instance
- Modify a Test Instance file to resolve a failing test
- Add features beyond the scope of the current Test Instance
- Use technical implementation details inside a Test Instance
- Close a task as complete if the Test Instance's Acceptance Criteria are not met

---

## Context Drift Recovery

If you feel you have lost track of the original user requirements, run:

```
/utad-check
```

This will re-read the User Task tree and coverage matrix and re-anchor
your current work to the correct Test Instances.

